ce:section.ce:para:
In the present study, FTIR technique has been successfully used as a tool to study the As-induced alterations, which were indicated by perturbations in the IR band structure in Cicer arietinum L. subjected to As and/or C-dots. The IR spectra revealed that control and C-dots samples showed a band at 1635 cm−1 which is specific for amide-II; and it shifted to 1631 cm−1 in As, and As + C-dots treated samples. Common peaks were observed in all the spectra around 3300 cm−1 and 1633 cm−1 representing O–H stretching and –COOH group respectively (Fig. 2
                        ). The region 2100-2160 cm−1 is characterized with triple bond of nitriles. The IR spectrum showed a band at 2123 cm−1 in control samples while a band at lower wave-number (2111 cm−1) was observed in presence of C-dots, which was absent in As treated samples (Table 2
                        ). This is indicative of the sensitiveness of nitrile group towards As, which resembles the observations of D'Souza et al. (2008) under Cd stress. Region 1800-1500 cm−1 shows characteristic bands for proteins, whereas 1700-1600 cm−1 is specific for amide-I bands, which is mainly due to the CO stretching vibrations of peptide bond. The bands in the amide-I region provided insight into the protein secondary structure. The regions 1200–1250 cm−1 correspond to PO asymmetric stretching frequencies. In the present study, As treated samples showed an absorption band at 1248 cm−1 due to PO asymmetric stretching vibrations of PO2
                        − phosphodiesters, while it was absent in all other spectra. Similar results were also reported by D'Souza et al. (2008) in Padina tetrastromatica under Cd stress. Phosphate moieties adopt chelating properties and among the phosphate containing metabolites, sugar-phosphate esters are known to play a crucial role in metal/loid chelation (D'Souza et al., 2008). The regions 900–1200 cm−1 are mainly dominated by the groups which belong to carbohydrates and cellular polysaccharides. In the present study, As treatment showed polysaccharide bands at 1073 cm−1; on the other hand, As + C-dots showed bands at 1178 cm−1. Bands in this region showed changes in their position towards different wave-numbers upon sugar-As metalation. Hence, this technique is a reliable and efficient tool for studying the difference in the chemical nature of Cicer arietinum L. in response to As and C-dots.
